{{infobox Organization |name = ClearPath Foundation |image = Logo ClearPath Foundation.png |size = 275px |motto = Clean Energy. The Conservative Way. |formation = 2013 |type = [[501(c) organization|501(c)3 organization]] |location = [[Charlotte, NC]], [[Washington, DC]] |leader_title = CEO |leader_name = [[Jay Faison]] | revenue = $165,599,943<ref name="Ratings">{{cite web | url=http://990s.foundationcenter.org/990_pdf_archive/463/463891359/463891359_201412_990.pdf | title=ClearPath Foundation Inc. | date= | website=Foundation Center | accessdate=16 February 2018 }}</ref> | revenue_year = 2014 | expenses = $241,776<ref name="Ratings" /> | expenses_year = 2014 |website = {{URL|www.clearpath.org}} }}
'''ClearPath Foundation''' is a nonprofit organization based in [[Charlotte, NC]] and [[Washington, D.C.]] that is focused on "conservative clean energy". According to a press release, the organization was founded to propose and support policies that accelerate [[clean energy]] without expanding the size of government.<ref>{{cite press release|title=New National Poll Shows Strong Republican Support for Clean Energy Policies|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/clearpath-energy-poll-idUSnPnb7135F+81+PRN20150929}}</ref>
== History == ClearPath was founded by Republican entrepreneur and philanthropist [[Jay Faison]] in 2013 to change the [[conservative]] viewpoint on clean energy. After selling his majority stake in the audio-visual company SnapAV, Faison donated $165 million to start ClearPath, with a mission of "accelerating conservative clean energy solutions"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goode|first1=Darren|title=Republican pledges $175 million to push party on climate|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/06/republican-climate-change-jay-faison-118755.html|website=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ClearPath Foundation, About Us|url=https://clearpath.org/about-us/}}</ref>
== Activities ==
ClearPath advances its mission through "strategic grant-making, advocacy, and digital platforms", and focuses on energy policy, polling, and analysis.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/clearpath-ceo-calls-for-conservative-clean-energy-policy-solutions-in-the-state-of-the-union-address-300203448.html | title = ClearPath CEO Calls For Conservative Clean Energy Policy Solutions In The State Of The Union Address | last = ClearPath | website = www.prnewswire.com | access-date = 2016-02-27 }}</ref><ref>https://clearpath.org/about-us/</ref> ClearPath has conducted polling on Americans' attitudes towards clean energy with [[Kristen Soltis Anderson]], finding that "72% of Republicans support accelerating the development of clean energy".<ref>https://clearpath.org/polling/</ref>
== Principles ==
The ClearPath website lists five principles used for analyzing policy. ClearPath believes in "small government, [[free markets]], and American innovation", as well as pollution [[risk management]], [[cost-benefit analysis]] and [[energy security]].<ref>https://clearpath.org/about-us/</ref>
== Policy Areas == *[[Coal pollution mitigation]] and [[natural gas]] – the ClearPath Foundation argues for expanded use of natural gas and further development of [[carbon capture]], utilization and storage.<ref>https://clearpath.org/policy/clean-coal-and-gas-101/</ref> They focus heavily on streamlining pipeline permitting and exports, as well as increasing research on carbon capture.<ref>https://clearpath.org/policy/clean-coal-and-gas/#streamline-exports</ref> *[[Nuclear power|Nuclear energy]] – ClearPath proposes expanded use of nuclear power in the United States, calling it "one of America's greatest success stories".<ref>https://clearpath.org/policy/nuclear-101/</ref> In particular, they support existing nuclear plants, as well as advanced nuclear such as [[small modular reactors]] and [[generation IV reactors]]. In February 2016, ClearPath's CEO Jay Faison proposed developing "super-competitive, next-generation" nuclear reactors.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.triplepundit.com/2016/02/nuclear-gets-new-cheerleader/ | title = Nuclear Gets a New Champion | website = Triple Pundit: People, Planet, Profit | language = en-US | access-date = 2016-02-27 }}</ref> *[[Hydropower]] – ClearPath supports hydropower development, calling it "one of America’s most overlooked energy resources".<ref>https://clearpath.org/policy/hydropower-101/</ref> They propose expanding [[electrification]] of non-powered dams, hydropower financing reform, and permitting reform.<ref>https://clearpath.org/policy/hydropower/</ref> *[[energy development|Energy Innovation]] – They support increased basic energy research funding for the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] to accelerate development, and propose paying for increased research through expanded oil and gas drilling.<ref>https://clearpath.org/policy/innovation/#advanced-energy-trust</ref> They also propose giving private companies greater access to the DOE's [[United States Department of Energy national laboratories|national labs]].<ref>https://clearpath.org/policy/innovation/#national-labs</ref>
